^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Since I will be focusing on declarer play starting next month, let's talk about that first. It is best if declarer takes stock at trick 1. The hand is actually pretty easy, there is 1 club loser, and 2 hearts at most. And, if the Q of hearts is onside, there is only 1 heart loser. But, declarer should be careful about planning entries, because needs to get back to the hand twice, to take heart finesses. So winning the first spade in dummy is good. Because that preserves the ace of spades. the other potential entries are the 9 of clubs and ace of diamonds.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, the basic plan is to draw trumps, and then take the heart finesse. there is no reason to ruff a spade in dummy. At trick 2 angela can simply lead a club. if ducked, another club. She will then have 2 entries to her hand (2 aces) to take the heart finesse. On this particular hand, the Q of hearts is offside, but that doesn't mean you should not take the finesse. As with many hands, planning your entries is extremely important.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to the bidding. Although I only have 12 HCP, I have a really good hand. For those who use losing trick count, it is 5 losing tricks, the equivalent of about 18 points. And if you use Bergen Starting Points, it is worth 12 HCP + 3 length points + 1 quality suit for 16. |
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| So using either LTC or Bergen points, good enough to jump to 3@C, despite the 12 HCP. And, because angela has 2 aces and 9 points, she should bid 3N which is a good contract. There are 9 tricks to be had, 6 clubs 2 spades and a diamond. Because the Q of hearts is offside, with perfect defense, 2 hearts and then diamond switch, you can go down, but in real life it will make almost all the time.|
